<dl id="n25073b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25073b">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25073b"> 73(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ inniskilling ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n25073b"><li>FW 8.23 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n25073b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n25073b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n25073b">MS BL 47482a-95</ms> </li><li>JJA 44:023 <a name="a1A0yd" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#a1A0yd">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/a1A0yd.htm#n25073b">Draft: I.1&sect;1A.0+</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Ponsonby&apos;s brigade of heavy cavalry (the Union Brigade, as it was called, from its being made up of the British Royals, the Scots Greys, and the Irish <mark>Inniskillings</mark>) did this good service. <small> Edward Creasy, <a name="ECFD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ECFD"><cite title="source">The Fifteen Decisive Battles of the World</cite></a> (1915) 419</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Major-General Sir William Ponsonby was in command of the Union Brigade, at Waterloo. The brigade was so-called because it included an English, a Scottish and an Irish regiment. The brigade consisted of the 1st Royal and 6th Inniskilling Regiments of Dragoons in the first line, and the 2nd Royal North British Dragoons (Scots Greys, named after their distinctive horses) in reserve. Note that Joyce associates the Shem-Shaun-Shemshaun triplets (his &ldquo;lipoleum boyne&rdquo; with this bridgade. </mm> </dd></dl>
